Rating: 4
I am sure krosswaugh from Toronto cooks wonderful Mexican food. The title of this recipe does not say Mexican and there are so many good ratings for this dish that it has to have something good going for it. I found it a few years ago and have made it several times. It is a family favorite. I use about half the chipotle as the brand I get is quite spicy. When the ribs are done I take them out and pour the sauce into a strainer over a fat separator. I then pour all the broth back into the pot along with what stays in the strainer, leaving the fat behind. A fat separator is a great kitchen tool for recipes like this. I then add the green chillies and cook a short time so they still have some crunch. I think the lime gives it a nice bright flavor. Lime is common in a lot of Caribbean recipes in combination with peppers.

Rating: 4
Funnily enough I made up a similar flavor combination, but with regular chiles such as jalapeno/Serrano combo instead of the chipotle. Chipotle is pretty overwhelming, and I think over-used. (Think McDonalds has a chipotle sauce=gross) Other chilies work better with the lime/tomato flavor. Trim your ribs before hand, and cool them after you've cooked to desired tenderness. It is much easier to scrape off the fat after they've sat in the fridge overnight, but this is just a rich meal regardless. Short-ribs are an extremely fatty cut of meat. I actually add about 1 cup of water mid-cooking as well, because I love a lot of juicy, flavorful broth. YUM! This also freezes well, I've kept it for up to 6 months!

